Of this kind are the precepts, that our Parents are to be honoured; that our Children are to be brought up3 that the lives of our Neighbours are to be pre- served3 that what is committed to our Trust is to be restored. These are to· be observed for the most part3 but yet admit of exceptions: thus the command of a parent may be set aside by the command of God: there may be sufficient grounds for casting off a child, putting to death a neighbour3 we are not to restore a sword committed to us by a madman. The Stoics recognized this distinction of perfect Duties and common Duties.

In order to direct our Oonscience, we are as much as possible to refer our actions to those general sels-evident moral axioms.

Of this general Natural Law is to be understood what Cicero says, de Repab. III. 22. [See Elem. Moral. Art. 351.]
